# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thermochemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The **bond dissociation energy** (**BDE**, ***D*0**, or ***DH°***) is one measure of the strength of a chemical bond A−B.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] It can be defined as the standard enthalpy change when A−B is cleaved by homolysis to give fragments A and B, which are usually radical species.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The enthalpy change is temperature-dependent, and the bond dissociation energy is often defined to be the enthalpy change of the homolysis at 0 K (absolute zero), although the enthalpy change at 298 K (standard conditions) is also a frequently encountered parameter.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] To convert a molar BDE to the energy needed to dissociate the bond *per molecule*, the conversion factor 23.060 kcal/mol (96.485 kJ/mol) for each eV can be used.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] Nevertheless, bond dissociation energy measurements are challenging and are subject to considerable error.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The majority of currently known values are accurate to within ±1 or 2 kcal/mol (4–10 kJ/mol).
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] Moreover, values measured in the past, especially before the 1970s, can be especially unreliable and have been subject to revisions on the order of 10 kcal/mol (e.g., benzene C–H bonds, from 103 kcal/mol in 1965 to the modern accepted value of 112.9(5) kcal/mol).
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] Even in modern times (between 1990 and 2004), the O−H bond of phenol has been reported to be anywhere from 85.8 to 91.0 kcal/mol.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] On the other hand, the bond dissociation energy of H2 at 298 K has been measured to high precision and accuracy: *DH*°298(H−H) = 104.1539(1) kcal/mol or 435.780 kJ/mol.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The term *bond dissociation energy* is similar to the related notion of *bond dissociation enthalpy* (or *bond enthalpy*), which is sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] However, some authors make the distinction that the bond dissociation energy (*D*0) refers to the enthalpy change at 0 K, while the term bond dissociation enthalpy is used for the enthalpy change at 298 K (unambiguously denoted *DH*°298).
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The former parameter tends to be favored in theoretical and computational work, while the latter is more convenient for thermochemical studies.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] For typical chemical systems, the numerical difference between the quantities is small, and the distinction can often be ignored.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] For a hydrocarbon RH, where R is significantly larger than H, for instance, the relationship *D*0(R−H) ≈ *DH*°298(R−H) − 1.5 kcal/mol is a good approximation.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] Some textbooks ignore the temperature dependence, while others have defined the bond dissociation energy to be the reaction enthalpy of homolysis at 298 K.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The bond dissociation energy is related to but slightly different from the depth of the associated potential energy well of the bond, *D*e, known as the *electronic energy*.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] This is due to the existence of a zero-point energy ε0 for the vibrational ground state, which reduces the amount of energy needed to reach the dissociation limit.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] Thus, *D*0 is slightly less than *D*e, and the relationship *D*0 = *D*e − ε0 holds.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] For instance, Blanksby and Ellison cites the example of ketene (H2C=CO), which has a C=C bond dissociation energy of 79 kcal/mol, while ethylene (H2C=CH2) has a bond dissociation energy of 174 kcal/mol.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] This vast difference is accounted for by the thermodynamic stability of carbon monoxide (CO), formed upon the C=C bond cleavage of ketene.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The difference in availability of spin states upon fragmentation further complicates the use of BDE as a measure of bond strength for head-to-head comparisons, and force constants have been suggested as an alternative.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] Historically, the vast majority of tabulated bond energy values are bond enthalpies.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] More recently, however, the *free energy* analogue of bond dissociation *enthalpy*, known as the *bond dissociation free energy* (BDFE), has become more prevalent in the chemical literature.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The BDFE of a bond A–B can be defined in the same way as the BDE as the standard free energy change (Δ*G*°) accompanying homolytic dissociation of AB into A and B.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] However, it is often thought of and computed stepwise as the sum of the free-energy changes of heterolytic bond dissociation (A–B → A+ + :B−), followed by one-electron reduction of A (A+ + *e*− → A•) and one-electron oxidation of B (:B− → •B + *e*−).
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] Except for diatomic molecules, the bond dissociation energy differs from the *bond energy*.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] While the bond dissociation energy is the energy of a single chemical bond, the bond energy is the average of all the bond dissociation energies of the bonds of the same type for a given molecule.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] For a homoleptic compound EX*n*, the E–X bond energy is (1/*n*) multiplied by the enthalpy change of the reaction EX*n* → E + *n*X.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] Average bond energies given in tables are the average values of the bond energies of a collection of species containing "typical" examples of the bond in question.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] For example, dissociation of HO−H bond of a water molecule (H2O) requires 118.8 kcal/mol (497.1 kJ/mol).
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The dissociation of the remaining hydroxyl radical requires 101.8 kcal/mol (425.9 kJ/mol).
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The bond energy of the covalent O−H bonds in water is said to be 110.3 kcal/mol (461.5 kJ/mol), the average of these values.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] In the same way, for removing successive hydrogen atoms from methane the bond dissociation energies are 105 kcal/mol (439 kJ/mol) for *D*(CH3−H), 110 kcal/mol (460 kJ/mol) for *D*(CH2−H), 101 kcal/mol (423 kJ/mol) for *D*(CH−H) and finally 81 kcal/mol (339 kJ/mol) for *D*(C−H).
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The bond energy is, thus, 99 kcal/mol, or 414 kJ/mol (the average of the bond dissociation energies).
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] None of the individual bond dissociation energies equals the bond energy of 99 kcal/mol.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] According to experimental BDE data, the strongest measured single bonds are Si−F bonds.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The BDE for H3Si−F is 152 kcal/mol, almost 50% stronger than the H3C−F bond (110 kcal/mol).
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The BDE for F3Si−F is even larger, at 166 kcal/mol.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] One consequence to these data are that many reactions generate silicon fluorides, such as glass etching, deprotection in organic synthesis, and volcanic emissions.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The strength of the bond is attributed to the substantial electronegativity difference between silicon and fluorine, which leads to a substantial contribution from both ionic and covalent bonding to the overall strength of the bond.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] For the same reason, B–F bonds are also very strong, possibly stronger than Si−F, with the BDE for F2B−F computed to be 172 kcal/mol at the CCSD(T)/CBS level of theory.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The C−C single bond of diacetylene (HC≡C−C≡CH) linking two sp-hybridized carbon atoms is also among the strongest, at 160 kcal/mol.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The strongest bond for a neutral compound, including multiple bonds, is found in carbon monoxide at 257 kcal/mol.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The protonated forms of CO, HCN and N2 are said to have even stronger bonds, although another study argues that the use of BDE as a measure of bond strength in these cases is misleading.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] On the other end of the scale, there is no clear boundary between a very weak covalent bond and an intermolecular interaction.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] Lewis acid–base complexes between transition metal fragments and noble gases are among the weakest of bonds with substantial covalent character, with (CO)5W:Ar having a W–Ar bond dissociation energy of less than 3.0 kcal/mol.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] Held together entirely by the van der Waals force, helium dimer, He2, has the lowest measured bond dissociation energy of only 0.022 kcal/mol.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] Bonds can be broken symmetrically or asymmetrically.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The former is called homolysis and is the basis of the usual BDEs.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] Asymmetric scission of a bond is called heterolysis.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] In the gas phase, the enthalpy of heterolysis is larger than that of homolysis, due to the need to separate unlike charges.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] However, this value is lowered substantially in the presence of a solvent.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] The data tabulated below shows how bond strengths vary over the periodic table.
[src:thermochemistry/bond-dissociation-energy] There is great interest, especially in organic chemistry, concerning relative strengths of bonds within a given group of compounds, and representative bond dissociation energies for common organic compounds are shown below.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Calorimetry is performed with a calorimeter.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Scottish physician and scientist Joseph Black, who was the first to recognize the distinction between heat and temperature, is said to be the founder of the science of calorimetry.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Indirect calorimetry calculates heat that living organisms produce by measuring either their production of carbon dioxide and nitrogen waste (frequently ammonia in aquatic organisms, or urea in terrestrial ones), or from their consumption of oxygen.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Lavoisier noted in 1780 that heat production can be predicted from oxygen consumption this way, using multiple regression.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The dynamic energy budget theory explains why this procedure is correct.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Heat generated by living organisms may also be measured by *direct calorimetry*, in which the entire organism is placed inside the calorimeter for the measurement.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] A widely used modern instrument is the differential scanning calorimeter, a device which allows thermal data to be obtained on small amounts of material.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] It involves heating the sample at a controlled rate and recording the heat flow either into or from the specimen.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The concept of heat has intrigued scientists for more than 2500 years.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] In the Graeco-Roman era, Plato and Aristotle regarded heat as a manifestation of fire.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Newton proposed that it was transmitted by vibrations of the particles of aether, while Descartes described it as an accelerated motion of air particles induced by light.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Robert Hooke viewed heat as a property of matter arising from the motion of its parts.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] For centuries, the prevailing theory imagined heat as a self-repelling, weightless fluid called "caloric".
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The measurement of heat began to take shape about three centuries ago.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] In 1750, Georg Wilhelm Richmann formulated the first general calorimetric equation, later known as Richmann's law, allowing calculation of the equilibrium temperature of mixed substances of the same kind.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] A decade later, Joseph Black made a decisive contribution: in 1761, he discovered that adding heat to ice at its melting point or to boiling water did not change their temperature.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] His identification of latent and specific heat marked the birth of thermodynamics and introduced the distinction between heat and temperature.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] In 1782, Antoine Lavoisier and Pierre-Simon de la Place constructed the first ice-calorimeter, launching quantitative calorimetry.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] At least one recent publication has called this calorie-metabolism theory into question.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Notably, the ice-calorimeter was first called *the machine* until the word *calorie* was coined in 1789.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The next major advance came from Sir Benjamin Thompson in the 1790s.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Observing heat generated during cannon boring under water, he concluded that heat must be a form of energy, not a material substance.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This idea was quantified by James Prescott Joule, who in the 1840s determined the mechanical equivalent of heat.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Using falling weights to drive a paddle in an insulated liquid, Joule demonstrated that 4.184 joules of work produce the same heating effect as one calorie, establishing a numerical link between mechanical work and thermal energy.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Around the same time, in 1840, the chemist Germain Henri Hess formulated Hess's law, showing that the total enthalpy change of a chemical reaction is independent of the reaction path.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This principle remains fundamental to modern thermochemistry and calorimetry.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Finally, in the 1870s, Pierre Eugène Berthelot developed the first modern bomb calorimeter and introduced the concepts of endothermic and exothermic reactions.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Calorimetry requires that a reference material that changes temperature have known definite thermal constitutive properties.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The classical rule, recognized by Clausius and Kelvin, is that the pressure exerted by the calorimetric material is fully and rapidly determined solely by its temperature and volume; this rule is for changes that do not involve phase change, such as melting of ice.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] There are many materials that do not comply with this rule, and for them, the present formula of classical calorimetry does not provide an adequate account.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The thermal response of the calorimetric material is fully described by its pressure $p\$ as the value of its constitutive function $p(V,T)\$ of just the volume $V\$ and the temperature $T\$ .
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] All increments are here required to be very small.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This calculation refers to a domain of volume and temperature of the body in which no phase change occurs, and there is only one phase present.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] An important assumption here is continuity of property relations.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] To determine this latent heat, the volume change is effectively the independently instrumentally varied quantity.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This latent heat is not one of the widely used ones, but is of theoretical or conceptual interest.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The temperature is forced to change by exposure to a suitable heat bath.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This latent heat is one of the two widely used ones.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The latent heat with respect to volume is the heat required for unit increment in volume at constant temperature.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] It can be said to be 'measured along an isotherm', and the pressure the material exerts is allowed to vary freely, according to its constitutive law $p=p(V,T)\$ .
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] For a given material, it can have a positive or negative sign or exceptionally it can be zero, and this can depend on the temperature, as it does for water about 4 C.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The concept of latent heat with respect to volume was perhaps first recognized by Joseph Black in 1762.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The term 'latent heat of expansion' is also used.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The latent heat with respect to volume can also be called the 'latent energy with respect to volume'.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] For all of these usages of 'latent heat', a more systematic terminology uses 'latent heat capacity'.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The heat capacity at constant volume is the heat required for unit increment in temperature at constant volume.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] It can be said to be 'measured along an isochor', and again, the pressure the material exerts is allowed to vary freely.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This means that for an increase in the temperature of a body without change of its volume, heat must be supplied to it.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This is consistent with common experience.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Quantities like $\delta Q\$ are sometimes called 'curve differentials', because they are measured along curves in the $(V,T)\$ surface.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Constant-volume calorimetry is calorimetry performed at a constant volume.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This involves the use of a constant-volume calorimeter.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Heat is still measured by the above-stated principle of calorimetry.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This means that in a suitably constructed calorimeter, called a bomb calorimeter, the increment of volume $\delta V\$ can be made to vanish, $\delta V=0\$ .
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] From the above rule of calculation of heat with respect to volume, there follows one with respect to pressure.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] An early calorimeter was that used by Laplace and Lavoisier, as shown in the figure above.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] It worked at constant temperature, and at atmospheric pressure.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The latent heat involved was then not a latent heat with respect to volume or with respect to pressure, as in the above account for calorimetry without phase change.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The latent heat involved in this calorimeter was with respect to phase change, naturally occurring at constant temperature.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This kind of calorimeter worked by measurement of mass of water produced by the melting of ice, which is a phase change.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This calculation is done by mathematical integration along the progression with respect to time.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This is because increments of heat are 'additive'; but this does not mean that heat is a conservative quantity.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The idea that heat was a conservative quantity was invented by Lavoisier, and is called the 'caloric theory'; by the middle of the nineteenth century it was recognized as mistaken.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Written with the symbol $\Delta \$ , the quantity $\Delta Q(P(t_{1},t_{2}))\,$ is not at all restricted to be an increment with very small values; this is in contrast with $\delta Q\$ .
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This expression uses quantities such as ${\dot {Q}}(t)\$ which are defined in the section below headed 'Mathematical aspects of the above rules'.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The use of 'very small' quantities such as $\delta Q\$ is related to the physical requirement for the quantity $p(V,T)\$ to be 'rapidly determined' by $V\$ and $T\$ ; such 'rapid determination' refers to a physical process.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] These 'very small' quantities are used in the Leibniz approach to the infinitesimal calculus.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The Newton approach uses instead 'fluxions' such as ${\dot {V}}(t)=\left.{\frac {dV}{dt}}\right|_{t}$ , which makes it more obvious that $p(V,T)\$ must be 'rapidly determined'.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] denotes the time rate of change of temperature of the calorimetric material.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The increment $\delta Q\$ and the fluxion ${\dot {Q}}(t)\$ are obtained for a particular time $t\$ that determines the values of the quantities on the righthand sides of the above rules.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] But this is not a reason to expect that there should exist a mathematical function $Q(V,T)\$ .
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] For this reason, the increment $\delta Q\$ is said to be an 'imperfect differential' or an 'inexact differential'.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Some books indicate this by writing $q\$ instead of $\delta Q\$ .
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Also, the notation *đQ* is used in some books.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Carelessness about this can lead to error.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The quantity $\Delta Q(P(t_{1},t_{2}))\$ is properly said to be a functional of the continuous joint progression $P(t_{1},t_{2})\$ of $V(t)\$ and $T(t)\$ , but, in the mathematical definition of a function, $\Delta Q(P(t_{1},t_{2}))\$ is not a function of $(V,T)\$ .
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Although the fluxion ${\dot {Q}}(t)\$ is defined here as a function of time $t\$ , the symbols $Q\$ and $Q(V,T)\$ respectively standing alone are not defined here.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The above rules refer only to suitable calorimetric materials.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The terms 'rapidly' and 'very small' call for empirical physical checking of the domain of validity of the above rules.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The above rules for the calculation of heat belong to pure calorimetry.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] They make no reference to thermodynamics, and were mostly understood before the advent of thermodynamics.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] They are the basis of the 'thermo' contribution to thermodynamics.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The 'dynamics' contribution is based on the idea of work, which is not used in the above rules of calculation.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Empirically, it is convenient to measure properties of calorimetric materials under experimentally controlled conditions.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] For measurements at experimentally controlled volume, one can use the assumption, stated above, that the pressure of the body of calorimetric material is can be expressed as a function of its volume and temperature.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] For measurements at experimentally controlled pressure, it is assumed that the volume $V\$ of the body of calorimetric material can be expressed as a function $V(T,p)\$ of its temperature $T\$ and pressure $p\$ .
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This assumption is related to, but is not the same as, the above used assumption that the pressure of the body of calorimetric material is known as a function of its volume and temperature; anomalous behaviour of materials can affect this relation.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] For measurements at experimentally controlled temperature, it is again assumed that the volume $V\$ of the body of calorimetric material can be expressed as a function $V(T,p)\$ of its temperature $T\$ and pressure $p\$ , with the same provisos as mentioned just above.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Assuming that the rule $p=p(V,T)\$ is known, one can derive the function of ${\frac {\partial p}{\partial T}}\$ that is used above in the classical heat calculation with respect to pressure.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Thermodynamics developed gradually over the first half of the nineteenth century, building on the above theory of calorimetry which had been worked out before it, and on other discoveries.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] In terms of thermodynamics, the internal energy $U\$ of the calorimetric material can be considered as the value of a function $U(V,T)\$ of $(V,T)\$ , with partial derivatives ${\frac {\partial U}{\partial V}}\$ and ${\frac {\partial U}{\partial T}}\$ .
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Calorimetry has a special benefit for thermodynamics.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] It tells about the heat absorbed or emitted in the isothermal segment of a Carnot cycle.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] A Carnot cycle is a special kind of cyclic process affecting a body composed of material suitable for use in a heat engine.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Such a material is of the kind considered in calorimetry, as noted above, that exerts a pressure that is very rapidly determined just by temperature and volume.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Such a body is said to change reversibly.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] (4) another adiabatic change of volume from $V_{d}\$ back to $V_{a}\$ just such as to return the body to its starting temperature $T^{+}\$ .
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] This quantity is used by thermodynamics and is related in a special way to the net work done by the body during the Carnot cycle.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The net change of the body's internal energy during the Carnot cycle, $\Delta U(V_{a},V_{b};T^{+};V_{c},V_{d};T^{-})\$ , is equal to zero, because the material of the working body has the special properties noted above.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The quantity $C_{T}^{(V)}(V,T)\$ , the latent heat with respect to volume, belongs to classical calorimetry.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] It accounts for the occurrence of energy transfer by work in a process in which heat is also transferred; the quantity, however, was considered before the relation between heat and work transfers was clarified by the invention of thermodynamics.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] In the light of thermodynamics, the classical calorimetric quantity is revealed as being tightly linked to the calorimetric material's equation of state $p=p(V,T)\$ .
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] From this, further mathematical and thermodynamic reasoning leads to another relation between classical calorimetric quantities.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] No work is performed in constant-volume calorimetry, so the heat measured equals the change in internal energy of the system.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] The heat capacity at constant volume is assumed to be independent of temperature.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] Heat is measured by the principle of calorimetry.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] In *constant-volume calorimetry* the pressure is not held constant.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] If there is a pressure difference between initial and final states, the heat measured needs adjustment to provide the *enthalpy change*.
[src:thermochemistry/calorimetry] is the unchanging volume of the sample chamber.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In the International System of Units (SI), the unit of measurement for enthalpy is the joule.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Other historical conventional units still in use include the calorie and the British thermal unit (BTU).
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The total enthalpy of a system cannot be measured directly because the internal energy contains components that are unknown, not easily accessible, or are not of interest for the thermodynamic problem at hand.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In practice, a change in enthalpy is the preferred expression for measurements at constant pressure, because it simplifies the description of energy transfer.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] When transfer of matter into or out of the system is also prevented and no electrical or mechanical (stirring shaft or lift pumping) work is done, at constant pressure the enthalpy change equals the energy exchanged with the environment by heat.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In chemistry, the standard enthalpy of reaction is the enthalpy change when reactants in their standard states (*p* = 1 bar; usually *T* = 298 K) change to products in their standard states.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] This quantity is the standard heat of reaction at constant pressure and temperature, but it can be measured by calorimetric methods even if the temperature does vary during the measurement, provided that the initial and final pressure and temperature correspond to the standard state.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The value does not depend on the path from initial to final state because enthalpy is a state function.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpies of chemical substances are usually listed for 1 bar (100 kPa) pressure as a standard state.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpies and enthalpy changes for reactions vary as a function of temperature, but tables generally list the standard heats of formation of substances at 25 °C (298 K).
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] For endothermic (heat-absorbing) processes, the change Δ*H* is a positive value; for exothermic (heat-releasing) processes it is negative.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The enthalpy of an ideal gas is independent of its pressure or volume, and depends only on its temperature, which correlates to its thermal energy.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Real gases at common temperatures and pressures often closely approximate this behavior, which simplifies practical thermodynamic design and analysis.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The word "enthalpy" is derived from the Greek word *enthalpein*, which means "to heat".
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The enthalpy H of a thermodynamic system is defined as the sum of its internal energy and the product of its pressure and volume: $H=U+pV,$ where U is the internal energy, p is pressure, and V is the volume of the system; p V is sometimes referred to as the pressure energy Ɛp.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpy is an extensive property; it is proportional to the size of the system (for homogeneous systems).
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] As intensive properties, the *specific enthalpy* *h* = *H*/*m* is referenced to a unit of mass m of the system, and the *molar enthalpy* *Hm* = *H*/*n*, where n is the number of moles.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] refers to the enthalpy of each subsystem.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] A closed system may lie in thermodynamic equilibrium in a static gravitational field, so that its pressure p varies continuously with altitude, while, because of the equilibrium requirement, its temperature T is invariant with altitude.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] small element of volume within the system, for example, the volume of an infinitesimally thin horizontal layer.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The integral therefore represents the sum of the enthalpies of all the elements of the volume.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The enthalpy of a closed homogeneous system is its energy function *H*(*S*, *p*), with its entropy *S*[*p*] and its pressure p as natural state variables which provide a differential relation for d*H* of the simplest form, derived as follows.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] is a small amount of work performed by the system.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In a homogeneous system in which only reversible processes or pure heat transfer are considered, the second law of thermodynamics gives *δQ* = *T* d*S*, with T the absolute temperature and d*S* the infinitesimal change in entropy S of the system.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Furthermore, if only pV work is done, *δW* = *p* d*V*.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The above expression of d*H* in terms of entropy and pressure may be unfamiliar to some readers.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] With this expression one can, in principle, determine the enthalpy if Cp and V are known as functions of p and T.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] However the expression is more complicated than $\mathrm {d} H=T\,\mathrm {d} S+V\,\mathrm {d} p$ because T is not a natural variable for the enthalpy H.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] At constant pressure, $\mathrm {d} p=0$ so that $\mathrm {d} H=C_{\mathsf {p}}\,\mathrm {d} T.$ For an ideal gas, $\mathrm {d} H$ reduces to this form even if the process involves a pressure change, because *αT* = 1.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In a more general form, the first law describes the internal energy with additional terms involving the chemical potential and the number of particles of various types.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The differential statement for d*H* then becomes $\mathrm {d} H=T\,\mathrm {d} S+V\,\mathrm {d} p+\sum _{i}\mu _{i}\,\mathrm {d} N_{i},$ where μi is the chemical potential per particle for a type i particle, and Ni is the number of such particles.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The last term can also be written as *μi* d*ni* (with d*n**i* 0 the number of moles of component i added to the system and, in this case, μi the molar chemical potential) or as *μi* d*mi* (with d*mi* the mass of component i added to the system and, in this case, μi the specific chemical potential).
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The enthalpy *H*(*S*[*p*], *p*, {*Ni*}) expresses the thermodynamics of a system in the *energy representation*.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] As a function of state, its arguments include one intensive and several extensive state variables.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The state variables *S*[*p*], p, and {*Ni*} are said to be the *natural state variables* in this representation.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] They are suitable for describing processes in which they are determined by factors in the surroundings.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] For example, when a virtual parcel of atmospheric air moves to a different altitude, the pressure surrounding it changes, and the process is often so rapid that there is too little time for heat transfer.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] This is the basis of the so-called adiabatic approximation that is used in meteorology.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Conjugate with the enthalpy, with these arguments, the other characteristic function of state of a thermodynamic system is its entropy, as a function *S*[*p*](*H*, *p*, {Ni}) of the same list of variables of state, except that the entropy *S*[*p*] is replaced in the list by the enthalpy H.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] It expresses the *entropy representation*.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The state variables H, p, and {*Ni*} are said to be the *natural state variables* in this representation.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] They are suitable for describing processes in which they are experimentally controlled.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] For example, H and p can be controlled by allowing heat transfer, and by varying only the external pressure on the piston that sets the volume of the system.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The U term is the energy of the system, and the pV term can be interpreted as the work that would be required to "make room" for the system if the pressure of the environment remained constant.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] When a system, for example, n moles of a gas of volume V at pressure p and temperature T, is created or brought to its present state from absolute zero, energy must be supplied equal to its internal energy U plus pV, where pV is the work done in pushing against the ambient (atmospheric) pressure.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In physics and statistical mechanics it may be more interesting to study the internal properties of a constant-volume system and therefore the internal energy is used.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In chemistry, experiments are often conducted at constant atmospheric pressure, and the pressure–volume work represents a small, well-defined energy exchange with the atmosphere, so that Δ*H* is the appropriate expression for the heat of reaction.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] For a heat engine, the change in its enthalpy after a full cycle is equal to zero, since the final and initial state are equal.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In order to discuss the relation between the enthalpy increase and heat supply, we return to the first law for closed systems, with the physics sign convention: d*U* = *δQ* − *δW*, where the heat δQ is supplied by conduction, radiation, Joule heating.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] We apply it to the special case with a constant pressure at the surface.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In this case the work is given by *p* d*V* (where p is the pressure at the surface, d*V* is the increase of the volume of the system).
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Cases of long-range electromagnetic interaction require further state variables in their formulation and are not considered here.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] If the system is under constant pressure, d*p* = 0 and consequently, the increase in enthalpy of the system is equal to the heat added: $\mathrm {d} H=\delta Q.$ This is why the now-obsolete term *heat content* was used for enthalpy in the 19th century.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In thermodynamics, one can calculate enthalpy by determining the requirements for creating a system from "nothingness"; the mechanical work required, pV, differs based upon the conditions that obtain during the creation of the thermodynamic system.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Energy must be supplied to remove particles from the surroundings to make space for the creation of the system, assuming that the pressure p remains constant; this is the pV term.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The supplied energy must also provide the change in internal energy U, which includes activation energies, ionization energies, mixing energies, vaporization energies, chemical bond energies, and so forth.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Together, these constitute the change in the enthalpy U + pV.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] For systems at constant pressure, with no external work done other than the pV work, the change in enthalpy is the heat received by the system.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] For a simple system with a constant number of particles at constant pressure, the difference in enthalpy is the maximum amount of thermal energy derivable from an isobaric thermodynamic process.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The total enthalpy of a system cannot be measured directly; the *enthalpy change* of a system is measured instead.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] For an exothermic reaction at constant pressure, the system's change in enthalpy, Δ*H*, is negative due to the products of the reaction having a smaller enthalpy than the reactants, and equals the heat released in the reaction if no electrical or mechanical work is done.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In other words, the overall decrease in enthalpy is achieved by the generation of heat.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Conversely, for a constant-pressure endothermic reaction, Δ*H* is positive and equal to the heat *absorbed* in the reaction.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] From the definition of enthalpy as H = U + pV, the enthalpy change at constant pressure is Δ*H* = Δ*U* + *p* Δ*V*.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] However, for most chemical reactions, the work term *p* Δ*V* is much smaller than the internal energy change Δ*U*, which is approximately equal to Δ*H*.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] As an example, for the combustion of carbon monoxide 2 CO(g) + O2(g) → 2 CO2(g), Δ*H* = −566.0 kJ and Δ*U* = −563.5 kJ.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Since the differences are so small, reaction enthalpies are often described as reaction energies and analyzed in terms of bond energies.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The *specific enthalpy* of a uniform system is defined as *h* = *H*/*m*, where m is the mass of the system.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] It can be expressed in other specific quantities by *h* = *u* + *pv*, where u is the specific internal energy, p is the pressure, and v is specific volume, which is equal to 1/*ρ*, where ρ is the density.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] An enthalpy change describes the change in enthalpy observed in the constituents of a thermodynamic system when undergoing a transformation or chemical reaction.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] It is the difference between the enthalpy after the process has completed, i.e. the enthalpy of the products assuming that the reaction goes to completion, and the initial enthalpy of the system, namely the reactants.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] These processes are specified solely by their initial and final states, so that the enthalpy change for the reverse is the negative of that for the forward process.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] A common standard enthalpy change is the enthalpy of formation, which has been determined for a large number of substances.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpy changes are routinely measured and compiled in chemical and physical reference works, such as the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The following is a selection of enthalpy changes commonly recognized in thermodynamics.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] When used in these recognized terms the qualifier *change* is usually dropped and the property is simply termed *enthalpy of "process"*.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] For such standardized values the name of the enthalpy is commonly prefixed with the term *standard*, e.g.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpy of reaction is defined as the enthalpy change observed in a constituent of a thermodynamic system when one mole of substance reacts completely.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpy of formation is defined as the enthalpy change observed in a constituent of a thermodynamic system when one mole of a compound is formed from its elementary antecedents.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpy of combustion is defined as the enthalpy change observed in a constituent of a thermodynamic system when one mole of a substance burns completely with oxygen.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpy of hydrogenation is defined as the enthalpy change observed in a constituent of a thermodynamic system when one mole of an unsaturated compound reacts completely with an excess of hydrogen to form a saturated compound.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpy of atomization is defined as the enthalpy change required to separate one mole of a substance into its constituent atoms completely.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpy of neutralization is defined as the enthalpy change observed in a constituent of a thermodynamic system when one mole of water is formed when an acid and a base react.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Standard enthalpy of solution is defined as the enthalpy change observed in a constituent of a thermodynamic system when one mole of a solute is dissolved completely in an excess of solvent, so that the solution is at infinite dilution.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Standard enthalpy of denaturation is defined as the enthalpy change required to denature one mole of compound.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpy of hydration is defined as the enthalpy change observed when one mole of gaseous ions is completely dissolved in water forming one mole of aqueous ions.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpy of fusion is defined as the enthalpy change required to completely change the state of one mole of substance from solid to liquid.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpy of vaporization is defined as the enthalpy change required to completely change the state of one mole of substance from liquid to gas.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpy of sublimation is defined as the enthalpy change required to completely change the state of one mole of substance from solid to gas.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Lattice enthalpy is defined as the energy required to separate one mole of an ionic compound into separated gaseous ions to an infinite distance apart (meaning no force of attraction).
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Enthalpy of mixing is defined as the enthalpy change upon mixing of two (non-reacting) chemical substances.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In thermodynamic open systems, mass (of substances) may flow in and out of the system boundaries.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The region of space enclosed by the boundaries of the open system is usually called a control volume, and it may or may not correspond to physical walls.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] There are then two types of work performed: *flow work* described above, which is performed on the fluid (this is also often called *pV work*), and *mechanical work* (*shaft work*), which may be performed on some mechanical device such as a turbine or pump.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] If we allow also the system boundary to move (e.g. due to moving pistons), we get a rather general form of the first law for open systems.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The term d*V**k*/d*t* represents the rate of change of the system volume at position k that results in pV power done by the system.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The parameter P represents all other forms of power done by the system such as shaft power, but it can also be, say, electric power produced by an electrical power plant.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Note that the previous expression holds true only if the kinetic energy flow rate is conserved between system inlet and outlet.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Otherwise, it has to be included in the enthalpy balance.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] During steady-state operation of a device (such as a turbine, pump, or engine), the average d*U*/d*t* may be set equal to zero.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The technical importance of the enthalpy is directly related to its presence in the first law for open systems, as formulated above.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The enthalpy values of important substances can be obtained using commercial software.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Practically all relevant material properties can be obtained either in tabular or in graphical form.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] There are many types of diagrams, such as *h* − *T* diagrams, which give the specific enthalpy as function of temperature for various pressures, and *h* − *p* diagrams, which give h as function of p for various T.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] One of the most common diagrams is the temperature–specific entropy diagram (*T* − *s* diagram).
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] It gives the melting curve and saturated liquid and vapor values together with isobars and isenthalps.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] These diagrams are powerful tools in the hands of the thermal engineer.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The points **a** through **h** in the figure play a role in the discussion in this section.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Points **e** and **g** are saturated liquids, and point **h** is a saturated gas.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] One of the simple applications of the concept of enthalpy is the so-called throttling process, also known as Joule–Thomson expansion.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] It concerns a steady adiabatic flow of a fluid through a flow resistance (valve, porous plug, or any other type of flow resistance) as shown in the figure.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] This process is very important, since it is at the heart of domestic refrigerators, where it is responsible for the temperature drop between ambient temperature and the interior of the refrigerator.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] It is also the final stage in many types of liquefiers.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] For a steady state flow regime, the enthalpy of the system (dotted rectangle) has to be constant.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] that is, the enthalpy per unit mass does not change during the throttling.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The consequences of this relation can be demonstrated using the T − s diagram above.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Point **c** is at 200 bar and room temperature (300 K).
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] A Joule–Thomson expansion from 200 bar to 1 bar follows a curve of constant enthalpy of roughly 425 ⁠ kJ /kg⁠ (not shown in the diagram) lying between the 400 and 450 ⁠ kJ /kg⁠ isenthalps and ends in point **d**, which is at a temperature of about 270 K.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Hence the expansion from 200 bar to 1 bar cools nitrogen from 300 K to 270 K.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In the valve, there is a lot of friction, and a lot of entropy is produced, but still the final temperature is below the starting value.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Point **e** is chosen so that it is on the saturated liquid line with *h* = 100 ⁠ kJ /kg⁠.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] It corresponds roughly with *p* = 13 bar and *T* = 108 K.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Throttling from this point to a pressure of 1 bar ends in the two-phase region (point **f**).
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] This means that a mixture of gas and liquid leaves the throttling valve.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Since the enthalpy is an extensive parameter, the enthalpy in **f** ( *h***f** ) is equal to the enthalpy in **g** ( *h***g** ) multiplied by the liquid fraction in **f** ( *x***f** ) plus the enthalpy in **h** ( *h***h** ) multiplied by the gas fraction in **f** (1 − *x***f** ).
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] This means that the mass fraction of the liquid in the liquid–gas mixture that leaves the throttling valve is 64%.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] A power P is applied e.g. as electrical power.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] If the compression is adiabatic, the gas temperature goes up.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In the reversible case it would be at constant entropy, which corresponds with a vertical line in the *T* − *s* diagram.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] For example, compressing nitrogen from 1 bar (point **a**) to 2 bar (point **b**) would result in a temperature increase from 300 K to 380 K.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In order to let the compressed gas exit at ambient temperature *T*a, heat exchange, e.g. by cooling water, is necessary.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] In the ideal case the compression is isothermal.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The average heat flow to the surroundings is Q̇.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The minimal power needed for the compression is realized if the compression is reversible.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The term *enthalpy* was coined relatively late in the history of thermodynamics, in the early 20th century.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Energy was introduced in a modern sense by Thomas Young in 1802, while entropy by Rudolf Clausius in 1865.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] *Energy* uses the root of the Greek word ἔργον (*ergon*), meaning "work", to express the idea of capacity to perform work.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] *Entropy* uses the Greek word τροπή (*tropē*) meaning *transformation* or *turning*.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] *Enthalpy* uses the root of the Greek word θάλπος (*thalpos*) "warmth, heat".
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The term expresses the obsolete concept of *heat content*, as d*H* refers to the amount of heat gained in a process at constant pressure only, but not in the general case when pressure is variable.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Gibbs used the term "a heat function for constant pressure" for clarity.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Introduction of the concept of "heat content" H is associated with Benoît Paul Émile Clapeyron and Rudolf Clausius (Clausius–Clapeyron relation, 1850).
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The term *enthalpy* first appeared in print in 1909.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] It is attributed to Heike Kamerlingh Onnes, who most likely introduced it orally the year before, at the first meeting of the Institute of Refrigeration in Paris.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] It gained currency only in the 1920s, notably with the *Mollier Steam Tables and Diagrams*, published in 1927.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] Until the 1920s, the symbol H was used, somewhat inconsistently, for "heat" in general.
[src:thermochemistry/enthalpy] The definition of H as strictly limited to enthalpy or "heat content at constant pressure" was formally proposed by A.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] In physical chemistry and thermodynamics, **Hess's law of constant heat summation**, also known simply as **Hess's law**, is a scientific law named after Germain Hess, a Swiss-born Russian chemist and physician who published it in 1840.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] The law states that the total enthalpy change during the complete course of a chemical reaction is independent of the sequence of steps taken.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] Hess's law is now understood as an expression of the fact that the enthalpy of a chemical process is independent of the path taken from the initial to the final state (i.e. enthalpy is a state function).
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] According to the first law of thermodynamics, the enthalpy change in a system due to a reaction at constant pressure is equal to the heat absorbed (or the negative of the heat released), which can be determined by calorimetry for many reactions.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] The values are usually stated for reactions with the same initial and final temperatures and pressures (while conditions are allowed to vary during the course of the reactions).
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] Hess's law can be used to determine the overall energy required for a chemical reaction that can be divided into synthetic steps that are individually easier to characterize.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] This affords the compilation of standard enthalpies of formation, which may be used to predict the enthalpy change in complex synthesis.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] Hess's law states that the change of enthalpy in a chemical reaction is the same regardless of whether the reaction takes place in one step or several steps, provided the initial and final states of the reactants and products are the same.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] Enthalpy is an extensive property, meaning that its value is proportional to the system size.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] Because of this, the enthalpy change is proportional to the number of moles participating in a given reaction.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] In other words, if a chemical change takes place by several different routes, the overall enthalpy change is the same, regardless of the route by which the chemical change occurs (provided the initial and final condition are the same).
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] If this were not true, then one could violate the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] Hess's law allows the enthalpy change (Δ*H*) for a reaction to be calculated even when it cannot be measured directly.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] This is accomplished by performing basic algebraic operations based on the chemical equations of reactions using previously determined values for the enthalpies of formation.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] Combination of chemical equations leads to a net or overall equation.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] If the enthalpy changes are known for all the equations in the sequence, their sum will be the enthalpy change for the net equation.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] If the net enthalpy change is negative ( $\Delta H_{\text{net}}<0$ ), the reaction is exothermic and is more likely to be spontaneous; positive Δ*H* values correspond to endothermic reactions.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] Hess's law states that enthalpy changes are additive.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] The concepts of Hess's law can be expanded to include changes in entropy and in Gibbs free energy, since these are also state functions.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] The Bordwell thermodynamic cycle is an example of such an extension that takes advantage of easily measured equilibria and redox potentials to determine experimentally inaccessible Gibbs free energy values.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] Combining Δ*G*o values from Bordwell thermodynamic cycles and Δ*H*o values found with Hess's law can be helpful in determining entropy values that have not been measured directly and therefore need to be calculated through alternative paths.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] For entropy, the situation is a little different.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] Heat changes in phase transitions and allotropic transitions.
[src:thermochemistry/hess-s-law] Electron affinities using a Born–Haber cycle with a theoretical lattice energy.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] In chemistry and thermodynamics, the **standard enthalpy of formation** or **standard heat of formation** of a compound is the change of enthalpy during the formation of 1 mole of the substance from its constituent elements in their reference state, with all substances in their standard states.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] The standard pressure value *p*⦵ = 105 Pa (= 100 kPa = 1 bar) is recommended by IUPAC, although prior to 1982 the value 1.00 atm (101.325 kPa) was used.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] The superscript Plimsoll on this symbol indicates that the process has occurred under standard conditions at the specified temperature (usually 25 °C or 298.15 K).
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] Standard states are defined for various types of substances.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] For a gas, it is the hypothetical state the gas would assume if it obeyed the ideal gas equation at a pressure of 1 bar.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] For a gaseous or solid solute present in a diluted ideal solution, the standard state is the hypothetical state of concentration of the solute of exactly one mole per liter (1 M) at a pressure of 1 bar extrapolated from infinite dilution.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] For a pure substance or a solvent in a condensed state (a liquid or a solid) the standard state is the pure liquid or solid under a pressure of 1 bar.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] For elements that have multiple allotropes, the reference state usually is chosen to be the form in which the element is most stable under 1 bar of pressure.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] One exception is phosphorus, for which the most stable form at 1 bar is black phosphorus, but white phosphorus is chosen as the standard reference state for zero enthalpy of formation.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] All elements are written in their standard states, and one mole of product is formed.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] This is true for all enthalpies of formation.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] The standard enthalpy of formation is measured in units of energy per amount of substance, usually stated in kilojoule per mole (kJ mol−1), but also in kilocalorie per mole, joule per mole or kilocalorie per gram (any combination of these units conforming to the energy per mass or amount guideline).
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] All elements in their reference states (oxygen gas, solid carbon in the form of graphite, etc.) have a standard enthalpy of formation of zero, as there is no change involved in their formation.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] The formation reaction is a constant pressure and constant temperature process.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] Since the pressure of the standard formation reaction is fixed at 1 bar, the standard formation enthalpy or reaction heat is a function of temperature.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] For tabulation purposes, standard formation enthalpies are all given at a single temperature: 298 K, and are represented by the symbol Δf*H*⦵ 298 K (or Δ*H*⦵ f,298 K).
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] For many substances, the formation reaction may be considered as the sum of a number of simpler reactions, either real or fictitious.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] The enthalpy of reaction can then be analyzed by applying Hess' law, which states that the *sum* of the enthalpy changes for a number of individual reaction steps equals the enthalpy change of the overall reaction.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] This is true because enthalpy is a state function, whose value for an overall process depends only on the initial and final states and not on any intermediate states.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] Examples are given in the following sections.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] For ionic compounds, the standard enthalpy of formation is equivalent to the sum of several terms included in the Born–Haber cycle.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] IELi, the first ionization energy of gaseous lithium.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] B(F–F), the standard enthalpy of atomization (or bond energy) of fluorine gas.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] EAF, the electron affinity of a fluorine atom.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] UL, the lattice energy of lithium fluoride.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] In practice, the enthalpy of formation of lithium fluoride can be determined experimentally, but the lattice energy cannot be measured directly.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] The formation reactions for most organic compounds are hypothetical.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] For instance, carbon and hydrogen will not directly react to form methane (CH4), so that the standard enthalpy of formation cannot be measured directly.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] However the standard enthalpy of combustion is readily measurable using bomb calorimetry.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] The standard enthalpy of formation is then determined using Hess's law.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] The negative sign shows that the reaction, if it were to proceed, would be exothermic; that is, methane is enthalpically more stable than hydrogen gas and carbon.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] It is possible to predict heats of formation for simple unstrained organic compounds with the heat of formation group additivity method.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] The standard enthalpy change of any reaction can be calculated from the standard enthalpies of formation of reactants and products using Hess's law.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] A given reaction is considered as the decomposition of all reactants into elements in their standard states, followed by the formation of all products.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] If the standard enthalpy of the products is less than the standard enthalpy of the reactants, the standard enthalpy of reaction is negative.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] This implies that the reaction is exothermic.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] The converse is also true; the standard enthalpy of reaction is positive for an endothermic reaction.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] This calculation has a tacit assumption of ideal solution between reactants and products where the enthalpy of mixing is zero.
[src:thermochemistry/standard-enthalpy-of-formation] which is the equation in the previous section for the enthalpy of combustion $\Delta _{\text{comb}}H^{\ominus }$ .
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] Endothermic reactions absorb heat, while exothermic reactions release heat.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] Thermochemistry coalesces the concepts of thermodynamics with the concept of energy in the form of chemical bonds.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] The subject commonly includes calculations of such quantities as heat capacity, heat of combustion, heat of formation, enthalpy, entropy, and free energy.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] Thermochemistry is one part of the broader field of chemical thermodynamics, which deals with the exchange of all forms of energy between system and surroundings, including not only heat but also various forms of work, as well the exchange of matter.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] When all forms of energy are considered, the concepts of exothermic and endothermic reactions are generalized to exergonic reactions and endergonic reactions.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] Thermochemistry rests on two generalizations.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] Hess' law of constant heat summation (1840): The energy change accompanying any transformation is the same whether the process occurs in one step or many.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] These statements preceded the first law of thermodynamics (1845) and helped in its formulation.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] Thermochemistry also involves the measurement of the latent heat of phase transitions.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] Joseph Black had already introduced the concept of latent heat in 1761, based on the observation that heating ice at its melting point did not raise the temperature but instead caused some ice to melt.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] Gustav Kirchhoff showed in 1858 that the variation of the heat of reaction is given by the difference in heat capacity between products and reactants: dΔH / dT = ΔCp.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] Integration of this equation permits the evaluation of the heat of reaction at one temperature from measurements at another temperature.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] The measurement of heat changes is performed using calorimetry, usually an enclosed chamber within which the change to be examined occurs.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] The temperature of the chamber is monitored either using a thermometer or thermocouple, and the temperature plotted against time to give a graph from which fundamental quantities can be calculated.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] Modern calorimeters are frequently supplied with automatic devices to provide a quick read-out of information, one example being the differential scanning calorimeter.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] Several thermodynamic definitions are very useful in thermochemistry.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] A system is the specific portion of the universe that is being studied.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] Everything outside the system is considered the surroundings or environment.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] A system undergoes a process when one or more of its properties changes.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] A process relates to the change of state.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] An isothermal (same-temperature) process occurs when temperature of the system remains constant.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] An isobaric (same-pressure) process occurs when the pressure of the system remains constant.
[src:thermochemistry/thermochemistry] A process is adiabatic when no heat exchange occurs.
